    <title>A.Human is a sci-fi fashion show about changing your body instead of your clothes</title>
    <content type="html">  
    &lt;img alt="Viper &amp;lt;em&amp;gt;is part of A. Human’s ‘biological heel’ series. It is displayed here on a live model.&amp;lt;/em&amp;gt;" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/u5NVB6ZHhgz_x88dz7FSxGYkU-I=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/61381733/akrales_180905_2922_0230_02.0.jpg" /&gt;



  		 &lt;p class="p-dropcap has-dropcap" id="L5TBdL"&gt;I spent at least half an hour wandering &lt;a href="https://www.ahumanbody.com/"&gt;&lt;em&gt;A.Human&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt; — an art installation about a futuristic body modification fashion house — before realizing one of the models was a human being. This wasn’t totally unreasonable: he was mostly hidden behind a wall, revealing only a torso embellished with glowing lines. According to a small sign beside him, the lines were transdermal blacklight implants designed as club wear, which the label’s mysterious designer A. Huxley had dubbed “Carnaval.” I realized my mistake when I looked closer and saw his muscles twitch.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="sqhwTK"&gt;&lt;em&gt;A.Human&lt;/em&gt; is full of these reverse-uncanny-valley moments. The installation, which opened last week and runs through the end of September, feels like something David Cronenberg might create if he...&lt;/p&gt;
